{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17145"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17145"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.57,0.03,0.18,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77232"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9835"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6812"},{"type":"tags","id":"8628"},{"type":"tags","id":"9843"},{"type":"tags","id":"9847"},{"type":"tags","id":"9849"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23038"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77232"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen ovale is a vital structure in foetal circulation that allows blood to bypass the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of foramen ovale closure at birth?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate fusion of septal tissues at first breath","Left atrial pressure exceeds right atrial pressure","Active muscular contraction closes the opening","Prostaglandin-mediated closure","Right atrial pressure exceeds left atrial pressure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt birth, \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft atrial pressure exceeds right atrial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E due to decreased pulmonary vascular resistance and increased blood flow to the left atrium. This pushes the septum primum against the septum secundum, creating a functional closure of the foramen ovale. Anatomical fusion of these tissues occurs gradually over several months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight atrial pressure exceeds left atrial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the foetal pattern that keeps the foramen ovale open\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive muscular contraction closes the opening\u003C/strong\u003E - The closure is passive, depending on pressure changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandin-mediated closure \u003C/strong\u003E- Prostaglandins are not relevant to foramen ovale closure; they are important in maintaining patency of the ductus arteriosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgrammed cell death of valve tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - The foramen ovale closes through mechanical pressure changes, not through apoptosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pressure changes occur due to the baby\u0027s first breaths, which decreases pulmonary vascular resistance therefore increasing pulmonary blood flow and venous return to the left atrium. This reverses the foetal circulation pattern and initiates closure of the foramen ovale.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The foramen ovale closes functionally at birth due to increased left atrial pressure exceeding right atrial pressure.","Anatomical closure of the foramen ovale occurs over several months through fusion of the septum primum and septum secundum.","Changes in pressure gradients at birth occur due to decreased pulmonary vascular resistance and subsequent increased pulmonary blood flow."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17145"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T13:46:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T13:47:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9835"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77232"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"}